<subSubSection id="C32415ECCE13FFCCFF6BC005FAD6FAEC" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B814667CE13FFCCFF6BC005FDFAFEAC" blockId="53.[151,1436,338,1844]" box="[151,618,338,364]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
Redescription, from 
<typeStatus id="5485F8C5CE13FFCCFE74C005FE63FEAC" box="[392,499,338,364]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">lectotype</typeStatus>
specimen
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B814667CE13FFCCFF3AC02DFAD6FAEC" blockId="53.[151,1436,338,1844]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
PUPARIUM. 
<emphasis id="B94A9A75CE13FFCCFE96C02DFE5EFE53" box="[362,462,378,403]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Habitus.</emphasis>
Original description said “body covered by coating of mealy wax and four pairs of shiny wax filaments which arise from the dorsum [from the large abdominal compound pores], and are many times the length of the body and make the insect very conspicuous”. 
<emphasis id="B94A9A75CE13FFCCFC34C09DFB8FFE23" box="[968,1055,458,483]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Margin</emphasis>
. Outline oval, 0.8 mm long, 0.5 mm wide, widest at abdominal segment IV (n=1). Margin irregular, not toothed. 
<emphasis id="B94A9A75CE13FFCCFB6EC0A5FB60FDCB" box="[1170,1264,498,523]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Dorsum</emphasis>
. Longitudinal moulting suture reaching puparial margin; transverse moulting sutures damaged (
<figureCitation id="13055AE2CE13FFCCFB96C34DFB55FDF4" box="[1130,1221,538,564]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–76" captionStartId="77.[151,269,1899,1923]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,204,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-62@77.[151,1436,194,1875]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURES 73–76. 73, Metaleurodicus essigi (Sampson &amp; Drews) comb. nov., lectotype puparium, Mexico, cephalothoracic plate. 74, M. essigi, lectotype, posterior dorsal detail. 75, M. essigi, lectotype, photomicrograph. 76, Palaealeurodicus antidesmae (Corbett) comb. nov., holotype puparium, Sri Lanka (after Corbett, 1926)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127296/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Fig. 75</figureCitation>
). Abdominal segment VII not significantly reduced medially. Abdominal segmentation distinct, especially between segments III/IV to VI/VII, where the division is visible almost to puparial margin (
<figureCitation id="13055AE2CE13FFCCFBE7C33DFBE7FD44" box="[1051,1143,618,644]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–76" captionStartId="77.[151,269,1899,1923]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,204,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-62@77.[151,1436,194,1875]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURES 73–76. 73, Metaleurodicus essigi (Sampson &amp; Drews) comb. nov., lectotype puparium, Mexico, cephalothoracic plate. 74, M. essigi, lectotype, posterior dorsal detail. 75, M. essigi, lectotype, photomicrograph. 76, Palaealeurodicus antidesmae (Corbett) comb. nov., holotype puparium, Sri Lanka (after Corbett, 1926)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127296/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Fig. 75</figureCitation>
). Pro-/mesothoracic and meso-/metathoracic divisions subtly visible submedially. Two pairs of thoracic cicatrices present (scars of third-instar compound pores, figure 73). Vasiform orifice (
<figureCitation id="13055AE2CE13FFCCFCADC3EDFC39FD14" box="[849,937,698,724]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–76" captionStartId="77.[151,269,1899,1923]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,204,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-62@77.[151,1436,194,1875]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURES 73–76. 73, Metaleurodicus essigi (Sampson &amp; Drews) comb. nov., lectotype puparium, Mexico, cephalothoracic plate. 74, M. essigi, lectotype, posterior dorsal detail. 75, M. essigi, lectotype, photomicrograph. 76, Palaealeurodicus antidesmae (Corbett) comb. nov., holotype puparium, Sri Lanka (after Corbett, 1926)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127296/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Fig. 74</figureCitation>
) rounded-cordate; operculum trapezoidal, its posterior margin very shallowly “m”-shaped, bearing a pair of stout setae; lingula head tongue-shaped, densely covered by seta-like spinules, bearing the normal 4 stout setae; lingula not reaching posterior puparial margin, but its setae overlapping margin. 
<emphasis id="B94A9A75CE13FFCCFD6EC265FC8EFC8B" box="[658,798,818,843]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Chaetotaxy.</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B94A9A75CE13FFCCFCD4C265FF58FCB4" bold="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">A probable anterior marginal seta visible on one side</emphasis>
. A pair of posterior marginal setae (
<quantity id="4CC6EB82CE13FFCCFD89C20DFD34FCB4" box="[629,676,858,884]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.6" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" unit="m" value="56.0">56µ</quantity>
long), and a pair of eighth abdominal setae (
<quantity id="4CC6EB82CE13FFCCFB4BC20DFB47FCB4" box="[1207,1239,858,884]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" unit="m" value="8.0">8µ</quantity>
long, anterior to vasiform orifice) present; submargin with 12 pairs of setae (including the nominal caudal pair), ranging from 
<quantity id="4CC6EB82CE13FFCCFF6BC2FDFF55FC04" box="[151,197,938,964]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" unit="m" value="15.0">15µ</quantity>
(anteriorly) to 
<quantity id="4CC6EB82CE13FFCCFE89C2FDFE34FC04" box="[373,420,938,964]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" unit="m" value="30.0">30µ</quantity>
(the posteriormost pair); 
<emphasis id="B94A9A75CE13FFCCFD32C2FDFAB7FC04" bold="true" box="[718,1319,938,964]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">submedian cephalothoracic setae entirely absent</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13055AE2CE13FFCCFACBC2FDFA1EFC04" box="[1335,1422,938,964]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–76" captionStartId="77.[151,269,1899,1923]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,204,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-62@77.[151,1436,194,1875]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURES 73–76. 73, Metaleurodicus essigi (Sampson &amp; Drews) comb. nov., lectotype puparium, Mexico, cephalothoracic plate. 74, M. essigi, lectotype, posterior dorsal detail. 75, M. essigi, lectotype, photomicrograph. 76, Palaealeurodicus antidesmae (Corbett) comb. nov., holotype puparium, Sri Lanka (after Corbett, 1926)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127296/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B94A9A75CE13FFCCFF6BC285FF4AFC2B" box="[151,218,978,1003]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Pores</emphasis>
. Cephalic and posterior two pairs of compound pores 
<quantity id="4CC6EB82CE13FFCCFCA3C285FC1DFC2C" box="[863,909,978,1004]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" unit="m" value="22.0">22µ</quantity>
in outer diameter, rather “bell-shaped” (
<figureCitation id="13055AE2CE13FFCCFA91C285FF28FBD4" captionStart="FIGURES 73–76" captionStartId="77.[151,269,1899,1923]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,204,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-62@77.[151,1436,194,1875]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURES 73–76. 73, Metaleurodicus essigi (Sampson &amp; Drews) comb. nov., lectotype puparium, Mexico, cephalothoracic plate. 74, M. essigi, lectotype, posterior dorsal detail. 75, M. essigi, lectotype, photomicrograph. 76, Palaealeurodicus antidesmae (Corbett) comb. nov., holotype puparium, Sri Lanka (after Corbett, 1926)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127296/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Fig. 74</figureCitation>
). Abdominal compound pores on segments III–VI extremely large, 
<quantity id="4CC6EB82CE13FFCCFC26C2ADFBA4FBD4" box="[986,1076,1018,1044]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" unit="m" value="70.0" valueMax="80.0" valueMin="60.0">60–80µ</quantity>
in outer diameter, each with a sword-like axial process. Immediately within puparial margin, on the abdomen only, lies a single row of widerimmed pores about 
<quantity id="4CC6EB82CE13FFCCFE70C51DFE3CFBA4" box="[396,428,1098,1124]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" unit="m" value="9.0">9µ</quantity>
in diameter (
<figureCitation id="13055AE2CE13FFCCFDB0C51DFD35FBA4" box="[588,677,1098,1124]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–76" captionStartId="77.[151,269,1899,1923]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,204,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-62@77.[151,1436,194,1875]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURES 73–76. 73, Metaleurodicus essigi (Sampson &amp; Drews) comb. nov., lectotype puparium, Mexico, cephalothoracic plate. 74, M. essigi, lectotype, posterior dorsal detail. 75, M. essigi, lectotype, photomicrograph. 76, Palaealeurodicus antidesmae (Corbett) comb. nov., holotype puparium, Sri Lanka (after Corbett, 1926)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127296/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Fig. 74</figureCitation>
), about 16 on one side of body and 18 on other (damage makes accurate count impossible); on the cephalothoracic plates pores of this type are absent (
<figureCitation id="13055AE2CE13FFCCFB5DC525FB6AFB4C" box="[1185,1274,1138,1164]" captionStart="FIGURES 73–76" captionStartId="77.[151,269,1899,1923]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,204,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-62@77.[151,1436,194,1875]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="FIGURES 73–76. 73, Metaleurodicus essigi (Sampson &amp; Drews) comb. nov., lectotype puparium, Mexico, cephalothoracic plate. 74, M. essigi, lectotype, posterior dorsal detail. 75, M. essigi, lectotype, photomicrograph. 76, Palaealeurodicus antidesmae (Corbett) comb. nov., holotype puparium, Sri Lanka (after Corbett, 1926)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5127296" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5127296/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B94A9A75CE13FFCCFAECC525FDEAFB74" bold="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Dorsal disc sparsely punctutated by loculate pores</emphasis>
and unassociated porettes, with a very few (slightly larger) loculate pores situated near puparial margin on cephalothoracic plates. 
<emphasis id="B94A9A75CE13FFCCFC89C594FC2EFB1C" box="[885,958,1219,1244]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Venter</emphasis>
. Ventral abdominal setae not discernible in 
<typeStatus id="5485F8C5CE13FFCCFF48C5BDFEB3FAC4" box="[180,291,1258,1284]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">lectotype</typeStatus>
. Legs typically robust and two-segmented, smooth, each with a pronounced apical claw. Antennal apices extending to bases of fore legs, their own bases anterolateral to fore legs. Tracheal folds absent.
</paragraph>
